<h3>Step 3: Use a Structured Review Prompt</h3>
<p>Don't just paste the contract and ask "is this okay?" A structured prompt produces a much more useful review. Here's a prompt that works well:</p>

<p>"You are reviewing a travel nurse employment contract. Please analyze this contract and provide: (1) A summary of the key financial terms including base hourly rate, overtime rate, housing stipend, M&amp;IE (meals and incidental expenses) per diem, and any tax-advantaged elements. (2) A list of any unusual clauses — particularly around cancellation penalties, non-compete restrictions, floating requirements, overtime calculation methodology, and at-will provisions. (3) A list of the 5 most important questions I should ask my recruiter before signing. (4) Any clauses that seem particularly favorable or unfavorable to the nurse. Here is the contract: [paste contract text]"</p>

<h3>Step 4: Review the AI Output Critically</h3>
<p>Read the AI's summary carefully. Pay special attention to any clauses it flags as unusual or potentially problematic. The AI may not catch everything, but it will catch the most common issues: problematic cancellation clauses, low strike pay provisions, float agreements that expand your scope significantly, and overtime calculations that use a blended rate methodology that reduces your effective overtime pay.</p>

<h3>Step 5: Ask Follow-Up Questions</h3>
<p>AI contract review is conversational. If the output mentions something you don't understand, ask about it. "What does 'blended overtime calculation' mean and how does it affect my take-home pay compared to overtime calculated on base rate only?" or "Explain what the 'loyalty clause' in section 7 would prevent me from doing after this contract ends."</p>

<h2>Key Contract Terms Every Travel Nurse Should Understand</h2>

<h3>Strike Pay / Cancellation Pay</h3>
<p>If the hospital cancels shifts, you typically receive "strike pay" — a reduced rate for the cancelled hours, often 40-50% of your full rate. The exact terms vary significantly by contract. Understand exactly how many cancellation hours per contract period are covered at what rate, and what happens if cancellations exceed that threshold.</p>

<h3>Housing Stipend Tax Status</h3>
<p>Travel nurse tax-free stipends (housing and M&amp;IE per diem) require you to have a legitimate tax home — a permanent residence in another state where you pay housing costs. The IRS has tightened enforcement of this in recent years. AI can explain the general framework, but for your specific situation, a tax professional who specializes in travel nursing is worth consulting. See our guide on <a href="travel-nurse-tax-software.html">travel nurse tax software</a>.</p>

<h3>Float Clauses</h3>
<p>Float requirements — where you can be assigned to work on units other than the one you were contracted for — vary dramatically by contract. Some float clauses are narrow (only to units with similar patient populations); others are broad (any unit in the facility). A broad float clause can put you in clinical situations significantly outside your competency area. Ask specifically: which units can I be floated to, and what is my right to decline if I don't have the competency for a particular unit?</p>

<h3>Non-Compete and Non-Solicitation</h3>
<p>Some travel contracts include clauses restricting you from working with the same hospital directly or through another agency for a defined period after your contract ends. These are more enforceable in some states than others, and their scope varies significantly. AI can explain what these clauses mean; an employment attorney can advise on enforceability in your state.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <strong>Comparison tip:</strong> When comparing two contract offers, paste both (de-identified) into Claude and ask: "Compare these two travel nurse contracts. Which offers better total compensation when housing stipend, M&amp;IE, and overtime structure are included? Which has more favorable terms around cancellation, float, and termination? Summarize the key trade-offs." This produces a structured comparison in under two minutes versus the hour it would take to build the same comparison manually.
</div>

